Forecast-based Financing (FbF) releases humanitarian funding based on forecasts for pre-agreed activities in anticipation of the occurrence of a disaster. In many cases this action in advance of rather than after a disaster, could reduce suffering, enhance preparedness and response, and contributes to a strengthened community resilience.Â 
Â 
The vision for FbA in Indonesia is to shift the current disaster management mindset of response to a disaster, to one that is â€˜response to a forecastâ€™-a shift that leverages current capacities and strengths and applies them to anticipatory approaches.
Â 
Support from AVIVA is helping PMI to realise this vision through funding to develop an Early Action Protocol to access funding for imminent threat in advance of a disaster occurring, based on a set of triggers, and pre-defined actions to be taken.

The Kenya Meteorological department forecast for December indicates that most parts of the country are expected to receive above average rainfall with parts of Western, Central and Rift valley having higher probabilities for above average rainfall. 9th Ebola epidemic outbreak in DRC in the Equateur region. BikoroÂ and Mbandaka city affected, this is the hub for regional exchanges, in proximity to CAR and Republic of Congo. A week after this was declared over, DRC were confronted with aÂ 10th outbreak in North Kivu Province. On 1 August 2018, the Ministry of Health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo notified WHO of a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in North Kivu Province, in the eastern part of the country. The province of North Kivu is among the most populated provinces, with eight million inhabitants. It shares borders with four other provinces (Ituri, South Kivu, Maniema and Tshopo) as well as with Uganda and Rwanda. (There is a tangible risk of EVD transmission in Uganda and Rwanda).Â The sub-region has been experiencing intense insecurity and worsening humanitarian crisis, with over one million internally displaced people and a continuous efflux of refugees to the neighbouring countries, including Uganda, Burundi and Tanzania. The protracted conflict context makes the emergency response activities more difficult because of restrained access and security risks. The EVD outbreak is rapidly evolving, with more new confirmed cases and deaths occurring. WHO regional risk raised to HIGH. Category of emergency (IFRC): RED Â  Â  RC launched a One International Appeal in May '18 fundraising for all RC components involved in the response (including ICRC). Appeal has been expanded several times, incorporating the response in Equateur, Eastern DRC and in all neighboring Priority 1 countries (Rwanda, Burundi, S.Sudan and Uganda).Â  Â

A 6.4 magnitude earthquake hit Albania at 3:54 AM local time on 26 November 2019, centred 30 km (19 miles) west of Tirana, at a depth of 10 km (6 miles). It was followed by a second one of 5.4 magnitude at 07:10 AM only a few hours later. The epicentre was around Durres (around 34 km northwest of Tirana). The earthquake has been described by authorities as the strongest to hit Albania in 30 years.
Â 

Since the earthquake struck on 26 November 2019, resulting in 51 deaths and up to 913 people injured, the Albanian Red Cross has been responding to the needs of the people affected. A total of 11,490 housing units were categorized as fully destroyed or demolished and need to be rebuilt. An additional 83,745 of housing units were either partially or lightly damaged. Approximately 17,000 people are displaced and are living in temporary accommodation. Most of the displaced households are staying in tents, host families or rented apartments.
Â 
The Government of Albania declared a state of emergency on 27 November 2019 lasting for 30 days, which was later extended until 31 March 2020.
Â 
The most affected administrative regions were the prefectures of DurrÃ«s, LezhÃ« and TiranÃ«. Structural damage has been widespread, yet focused on old buildings and on those built with poor building practice in the transition area of the 1990s and early 2000s. Additional administrative areas considered secondary affected are those where people have been evacuated to by the government, including Berat, DibÃ«r, Elbasan, Fier, KukÃ«s, Shkodra and VlorÃ«.
Â 
The Post-Disaster Need Assessment indicates that 5,080 buildings (including apartment blocks, single-family houses, hotels, schools, infrastructure, etc.) have been categorized under DS4 and DS5, equating to being uninhabitable.

After more than four years, the conflict in Yemen that has brought about a man-made humanitarian disaster affecting 22.5 million people.
Â 

As a result of the protracted violence, thousands of civilians have been killed or injured, and millions displaced. Widespread damage to public infrastructure and severe shortage of supplies, owing to restrictions on the movement of goods into and within the country, make it nearly impossible for the majority of Yemenis to obtain food, water, medical care and other essentials.
Â 
Wounded and sick people are unable to obtain timely and good-quality health services, because of the dangers associated with seeking such services. Most hospitals are seriously handicapped by the lack of medicines, equipment and trained staff. National capacities for tackling public-health emergencies, such as cholera outbreaks, are very limited.
Â 
Millions of people have been displaced since the conflicts began; many are still unable to return home. A large part of the population is heavily dependent on humanitarian aid and faces food insecurity. They struggle to obtain or produce food, and to resume or sustain their livelihoods, because of the fighting and movement restrictions. The unavailability of potable water and of adequate sanitation facilities puts many of them at risk of disease or illness.
Â 
Attacks against humanitarian personnel are not uncommon. Since the escalation of the conflict in March 2015, seven Yemen Red Crescent Society volunteers and three ICRC personnel have been killed while carrying out their duties. The few international organizations present in the country struggle to respond to the outstanding needs of victims.
